9","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","aproximadamente 1300":"circa 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Besthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Besthorpe, Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"en":{"aproximadamente 1300–":"about 1300–Deceased","1300–1349":"1300–1349","1325–1366":"1325–1366","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","aproximadamente 1300":"about 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Besthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Besthorpe, Norfolk, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Agnes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English; French (<b>Agnès</b>); Hungarian (<b>Ágnes</b>): from a female personal name, which is from Late Latin <i>Agnes</i> and this one from Greek <i>Hagnē</i>, from <i>hagnē</i> ‘pure, chaste’. Saint Agnes was a Christian virgin martyr, one of those who suffered under the persecutions of Diocletian in 303  AD . Her name was associated by folk etymology with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, and in medieval art she is often depicted with a lamb (the lamb of God). See also English   Annis  .","American shortened (and altered) form of rare Greek metronymics <b>Agnidis</b> or <b>Agniadis</b>, both derived from the female personal name <i>Hagnē</i> (see 1 above), or of patronymics like   Anagnostopoulos   (compare   Agnew   4)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ann","meanings":["habitational name from Abbots Ann in Hampshire, named for the stream that runs through it, which is most probably named with an ancient Celtic word meaning ‘water’.","possibly from the Middle English female personal name <i>Ann(e)</i>, which is normally a pet form of   Agnes   (Middle English <i>Annes</i>), since the Biblical homonym was not common before the 15th century.","English:"]},{"name":"Ines","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Doroteo, Acacio, Adolfo, Alejandro, Armando, Aura, Bernabe, Desiderio, Ernesto, Eustaquio, Gilberto, Jose.","Portuguese (<b>Inês</b>) and Spanish: from a vernacular form of the Late Latin female personal name   Agnes  .","Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Annese","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore, Cosmo, Domenico, Fedele, Marco, Nino, Pietro, Romeo, Sandro, Vito.","Italian: from a variant of <i>Agnese</i>, Italian form of the female personal name   Agnes  ."]},{"name":"Annis","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English female personal name <i>Annes</i>, Old French <i>Anes</i>, from Late Latin   Agnes  ."]},{"name":"D'Agnese","meanings":["Italian (also <b>Dagnese</b>): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Agnese</i>, from Late Latin   Agnes  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arderne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Ardern  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ardern","meanings":["English: locative name variant of   Arden  . Arden in Cheshire is recorded as  <i>Arderne</i> in 1260, and Arden in Warwicks is recorded as  <i>Arderne</i> in 1200."]}]},{"name":"Padre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Rafael, Carlos, Ramon, Andres, Angel, Efrain, Luz, Rolando, Ruben, Altagracia, Anabella.","Catalan (<b>Padró</b>):","variant of the topographic name <b>Pedró</b>, from <i>pedró</i> ‘memorial stone’ (see   Pedro  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Padron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Carlos, Alberto, Mario, Raul, Jorge, Roberto, Manuel, Rafael, Jesus.","Spanish (Tenerife; <b>Padrón</b>): in some cases, a variant of Catalan <b>Padró</b> (see   Padro  ); otherwise from the Spanish equivalent <i>padrón</i>, a variant of <i>patrón</i> ‘master’.","Galician (<b>Padrón</b>): habitational name from Padrón, a town in Galicia (Spain)."]},{"name":"Pedro","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Padre Agnes de Arderne was born about 1300, in England. He had at least 1 daughter with Philippa d'Oyly."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1300–":"umbes 1300–Surnud",